Food: Where European inflation slipped up
The skyward zoom in food prices is the main force behind the speedup in eurozone inflation.
October and November inflation rates were higher than expected in 13 eurozone countries, with October's 2.6 percent yr/yr inflation rate followed by 3.1 percent in November, the EU's Luxembourg-based statistical office reported.
Official forecasts predicted only 3 percent, Bloomberg said.
The European Central Bank (ECB) did not cut interest rates, arguing that a rate drop combined with rising raw material prices and declining unemployment would trigger an inflationary spiral.
The ECB wants to keep inflation under two percent or somewhere in that vicinity.
According to one analyst, ECB is in a Catch-22: It must talk down inflation to keep from having to take action to push it down later in the game.
Germany’s November inflation rate of 3.3 percent is a record; in Spain the rate rose to 4.1 percent from an earlier 3.6.
Food and energy prices soared into the stratosphere.
Wheat futures were up by 88 percent and soybean prices were at their highest since 1973.
Consumers also have to pay significantly more for vegetable oil and dairy products in 2007.
The world market price of crude oil rose by 52 percent this year, with black gold costing nearly 100 dollars a barrel last month.
The ECB predicts that 2008 inflation will climb to 2.5 percent from the previous 2.1, but will drop back to 1.9 percent in 2009.
Analysts see the 12-month inflation rate steadily rising at about 3 percent over the next 3-4 months, but estimate that the annual average rate will be 2.1 percent.
The ECB also predicts that it will cut interest rates two times during 2008.
