Many hospitals try to save by reducing disinfectant use.
Hospitals have registered over a thousand cases of infections caused mainly by inappropriate use of antibiotics.
Hospital cleanliness, overcrowding, and overburdened staff are not conducive to preventing infection, said the Division Head at the National Centre for Epidemiology.
Many places even try to cut back on disinfectant use to save money.
MRSA - antibiotic resistant staphylococcus - infection was recently diagnosed in the traumatology ward of János hospital.
The infection was detected in a man who was hospitalized after a major accident.
The patient was isolated.
The same hospital had to deal with similar infection early this year.
The hospital discharged a patient after a serious traffic accident, and shortly after, it re-admit the patient because of MRSA infection, and doctors have been unable to perform surgery that would be vital to full recovery because they have been unable to perform surgery that would be vital to full recovery.
This year, up to 10th December, hospitals have reported 1,094 cases of antibiotic-resistant pathogens to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, according to National Centre for Epidemiology physician Karolina Böröcz.
This tells us the number of antibiotic-resistant pathogens that hospitals actually included in their records, but nothing more.
About twothirds of the infections (683 cases) were caused by MRSAs, which is officially a methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
One third of all people carry the Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their nose without causing any infection.
The infections that SA cause (such as sore throat, tonsillitis, minor skin infections, and wound infections) respond well to antibiotics and can be treated.
However, if antibiotics are overused or inappropriately used, the bacteria that originally respond well to antibiotics can evolve into an antibiotic-resistant variety, which rapidly spreads in hospitals if hygienic conditions are low.
Particularly at risk are elderly and low-body-weight patients whose immune systems have been temporarily or permanently compromised. In these patients, the staph can cause serious nosocomial infections such as wound infections or sepsis.
According to János Hospital's medical director, there is nothing unusual about having an MRSA infection since they are part of everyday hospital life.
The infection is not a disease, Tibor Nyulasi says. MRSA will be found everywhere anyone goes to test for it, he adds.
Antibiotic resistance
Nurse staff wear rubber gloves and masks when working with infected patients.
When a patient is admitted to the hospital, one of the first things done is to check for MRSA, but hospitals are still vulnerable to infection.
Staph testing is not fashionable
The vast majority of nosocomial MRSA-induced infections can be prevented, but current hospital conditions are not conducive to preventing the evolvement and spread of antibiotic-resistant infections.
Since this type of infection typically occurs in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should routinely check all newly admitted patients and immediately isolate MRSA carriers.
However, taking microbiological samples from patients is not common in Hungary.
The reason is that the National Health Insurance Fund does not cover the cost of these tests.
In most cases the bacteria remain unnoticeable unless the patient has a clear MRSA infection, said the National Centre for Epidemiology physician.
The European Union has stringent protocols on the proper use of antibiotics in human medicine and Hungary has its own guidelines on treating various infections and pathologies.
The goal should be targeted therapy, meaning that microbiology tests should be conducted to prevent resistance from evolving, but hospitals do not always follow this.
It is even rarer to take a microbiology sample among outpatients in primary or specialized care, Böröcz added.
Save money by reducing antibiotics
Scientific evidence shows that most common way MRSA is transmitted from one patient to another through healthcare personnel who transport it from patient to patient.
Accordingly, washing hands, and wearing gloves and masks play a significant role in prevention, but again, there are many shortcomings in hospital practice.
MRSAs are transmitted through physical contact and body fluids. Under domestic hospital conditions, an infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In fact, hospital wards are often overcrowded, with beds too close to one another, but they should be at least 1.5 metres apart to conform to epidemiological requirements.
However, we also find that when hospitals are short on money they tend to save on disinfectants, adding that with a shortage of nursing staff and too many patients, infection increases.
According to Böröcz, there are demonstrably less infections and those that occur are easier to prevent from spreading, in hospitals that take appropriate protective measures.
Government programme to combat MRSA
MRSA infections cost the health insurance a huge amount of money, so efforts should be made to prevent them from occurring in the first place.
In the UK, the government has a programme to reduce MRSA and prevent its spread.
The programme seems to be successful as published data shows that MRSA is declining in the UK.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has set out the prevention of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and nosocomial infections as a priority project.
Police chief causing fatal accident was not drinking.
The official professional opinion has been submitted regarding a fatal accident caused by Budapest's District 22 police chief.
Attila Morvai, spokesman for the Budapest Municipal Prosecutor's Office, issued a statement on Friday, on receipt of the professional opinion.
Professional opinion supports the result of the preliminary investigation, which concluded that the former police chief had not consumed alcohol before getting on the road.
The former District 22 police chief was driving his own car in his district. He turned around a corner and hit a 55 year old man trying to cross Kossuth Lajos Street at a spot where no marked pedestrian crossing was visible.
The absence of an official crossing point is not a mitigating circumstance, since traffic rules require that drivers have the right to cross over a turning vehicle.
The pedestrian died shortly after arrival at a hospital.
The district police chief resigned after the accident and requested that he resign from the force because he was so shocked by the event.
The Budapest Prosecutor's Investigative Unit is conducting an investigation.
The former police chief has been cooperating with the prosecutors in the case, Morvai added.
Additional 400 million euros available for infrastructure
The amount of 100 million euros in loans will be available for education, transport, environmental infrastructure and energy development after three agreements signed by Finance Minister János Veres and European Investment Bank (EIB) Vice President Marta Gajecka in Budapest on Friday.
EIB approved a 300 million euros framework package in 2006 to help the Hungarian budget finance transport and environmental projects implemented by the cohesion fund. A concrete contract for 100 million from the package was signed in 2006, so one new contract covers the use of the remaining 200 million euros.
The second agreement, for 150 million euros, will help the budget finance education-related projects.
EIB has already approved a 300 million Euro package for Hungary to use for upgrades to these areas. The extra 150 million euros can be used later, when the credit agreement is extended.
The third agreement was for 50 million euros for innovation. The central budget plans to use it mainly in a R&D project at Debrecen University.
The talks included a new metro line under construction in Budapest.
The agreement was that when Hungary finalizes metro financing details with the EU, they would revisit the original contract to see if they needed to be changed, and if so, how.
However, he believed that the latter discussion would take place in the first quarter of 2008.
EIB has provided Hungary with the equivalent of 8.4 billion euros since 1990, which was used to finance 113 projects.
EIB is linking interest rates on the loans to EURIBOR, allowing an 8 year grace period, and is charging no commission to maintain fund availability.
Bulgaria: The EU's real estate paradises
The real estate market in Bulgaria has been growing at an unbelievable rate - Europe has its eyes on this once-rare Balkan nation.
What is buying and where on this market, which is still the cheapest in the EU despite rapidly rising prices?
This analysis is from RE/MAX Bulgarian division.
No question but that Bulgaria is the most sought-after East European real estate target, with its low-cost ski chalets and oceanfront homes.
The most fashionable mountain sites are Bansko, Borovets and Vitosha, while on the seaside the most popular areas are Albena, the Golden Sands and ancient Sozopol and Nesebar, but a growing number of investors are looking at real estate around Karvarna and Balcsik.
According to RE/MAX Bulgaria analysts, soon or later the central part of the country will start attracting investors.
Sofia, the capital, also has many attractive opportunities. Commercial and office space offer the highest returns.
Bulgaria is well on the way to be one of Europe's most exciting golf destinations.
Forward-thinking investors are already making major purchases, for example, in and around Bansko.
Analysts suggest that people who buy real estate in Bulgaria would also like to change their lifestyles.
Most investors are from the UK, but many also come from France, Belgium, and Spain, with a growing number coming from Romania.
Maltees and Cypriot investors have also gained foothold, while Russians are traditional big time buyers at the Black Sea and on top ski slopes.
There are three types of international buyers, said Regional Manager of RE/MAX Bulgaria Georgi Yankov.
The ones who plan to resettle in Bulgaria either purchase renovated properties for 50,000-100,000, or old fixer-uppers for 5,000-15,000 and then renovate them themselves.
Their purchases should be easy to access and equipped for modern communication.
Next group of buyers is interested in summer homes (Bulgaria joined Germany's top ten holiday destinations in December).
The fourth group includes investors for business purposes, who are counting on medium or long-term appreciation.
The prices in Sofia, the capital, are steadily rising, as is demand.
While Bulgaria boasts the European Union's lowest real estate prices, they have continued to rise by 21 percent in the past five years.
Actually, the rise in real estate prices has exceeded the growth in salaries.
EnviMin and Hungary's six percent estimated GDP
Climate Minister Gábor Fodor has announced that professional level meetings on post-2012 international climate issues will end on Tuesday. The conference will officially open on Wednesday, when the ministers take up the matter.
Political and policy makers from 192 countries are expected to discuss the Bali Roadmap, which focuses on efforts to reduce greenhouse gas emissions after the Kyoto Protocol expires.
In current developing and developed countries are in a heated dispute.
The United States has made it clear that it is unwilling to agree to precise numbers but it is not opposed to a 25-40 percent cut in greenhouse gases by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other big question at the conference is whether the developed countries are ready to reduce their emissions but also to offer financial and technological assistance to countries that need it.
One agreement was on support to developing countries.
The 16-member board will manage the funding for this, which is set by the Kyoto Protocol, and will most likely work in the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF).
Hungary’s six percent increase
Representative of Hungary, Environment Minister Gábor Fodor is ready to support EU efforts to maintain its flagship role in global climate protection effort and promote a new international agreement, to be signed by 2009.
According to Fodor, the EU is ready to cut greenhouse gas emissions by 2020 compared to 1990, if the "post-2012 agreement" is reached or not, and is ready to cut them by 30 percent if other major developed regions of the world and developing countries are also ready to accept obligations to the extent of their abilities and responsibilities.
Fodor added that in 1997, the countries adhering to the Kyoto Protocol had targeted a 5.2 percent reduction in overall emissions. In that group, the 15-member EU agreed to an 8 percent decline.
Hungarian government agreed to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent compared to 1985-1987, a goal it is aiming at, according to the Environment ministry's press release.
The stakes in Bali are high, for a long-term international climate policy agreement must be under wraps within two years or it will not be implemented by 2012.
The result could be a delay in emissions reduction, which would place Earth on a course towards an average temperature rise exceeding 2 degrees Celsius.
UK uses YouTube as military recruiting tool
British military units have been sharing their Iraqi and Afghanistani actions through video clips on You Tube in an effort to popularize their mission.
The Royal Air Force (RAF) was the first to develop a taste for YouTube: its special forces in Afghanistan have been uploading video clips showing how they have been combating the Taliban since March 2006, BBC reports.
The images, taken with miniature cameras attached to troop helmets, are monitored by a command centre in Kandahar and then sent to London from where they are uploaded on the Internet.
There is no mistaking the political message.
Fully 139 RAF images have been uploaded to the Internet and so far they have received over 75,000 hits.
The UK defence ministry has been registered as "defence headquarters" and regularly uploading video clips on Iraqi and Afghanistani actions, while the Commonwealth Office and the Multinational Force - Iraq (MNF-I) have their own You Tube channels.
Introduction Afghanistan
The RAF originally uploaded the videos as a recruiting tool, and the defence ministry says they have also been a good way to let the public know the real purpose of the RAF.
Advertising through this route costs almost nothing compared to traditional recruitment commercials on television, defence expert Gordon Mackenzie told BBC.
Americans have turned it into a game.
The problem the military has to deal with is the amateur videos being shared alongside the carefully edited and censured official clips, sometimes even showing dying soldiers.
The video clips from the Iraqi and Afghanistani battlefields have been posted on the Internet, but British forces have only recently joined the postings.
American recruiting is a bit different. The US has been using America's Army, a tactical shooting game available for free download, as a recruiting tool.
