Massive strike forces come together
On Friday, the Liga Unions and the National Federation of Workers' Councils (NWF) will form a strike committee to coordinate an open-ended strike which starts on Monday.
The group plans to hold a protest rally on Saturday and on Monday - the day parliament will vote on a health insurance bill - they will start their work stoppage.
The strike is certain to damage the transport network, as trains will become more or less completely stopped and Budapest public transport will be blocked until 1.00 p.m.
Working Council federation will publish details of their jointly organized Monday walkout on Friday afternoon.
A LIGA - MOSZ strike committee is being set up to coordinate Monday’s industrial action.
Organizers plan to hold a public protest demonstration on Saturday, and the organizations joining the strike will begin an open-ended work stoppage on Monday unless they can reach a prior agreement with the government.
What this means is that they have not set a termination date for the walkout, starting from the day parliament adopts the health insurance bill.
If parliament fails to adopt the health insurance law, the unions will immediately retract their strike appeal.
If they adopt the bill, the strike committees will meet and decide on their next move.
Given the parliament's agenda for Monday, it is possible that the health insurance bill may not come up for a vote until evening or possibly late at night.
The strike that starts on Monday is expected to cause significant delays in the transport system. The railways will stop running for an open-ended period, while a portion of Budapest public transport may be halted through noon, as well as half of the long distance bus lines.
The same time, partial roadblocks on many of the nation's highways will be added.
Many unions and civic organizations have responded to the strike appeal. A complete and regularly updated list of them is available on Liga's website.
Some organizations have announced open-ended strikes, while others are restricting themselves to temporary work stoppages.
The agreement was not reached between MÁV and the Railway Workers' Free Trade Union (VDSZSZ), despite the fact that a growing number of people plan to travel by rail as the Christmas holidays approach.
The Budapest Transport Company will be out from start work to 1 p.m., Budapest Airport will halt work from 7 to 9 a.m., Liga's Power and Thermal Energy Unions will walk off the job for 4 hours, while the Teachers' Union and the Democratic Union of Teachers will hold 2-hour walkouts.
The National Federation of Physicians will hold a nationwide strike over staggered hours, while the Democratic Union of Health and Welfare Workers (EDDSZ) is planning a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four demands is that the government repeal its health insurance reform bill and submit a new concept for public debate.
The second demand is that the new method for calculating pensions due to begin next year be introduced gradually, instead of all at once.
The fourth is that when determining the occupations eligible for early retirement, the jobs to be included in the option be selected before 2010.
The fourth reason for the strike is that the Railway Workers' Free Trade Union (VRSZSZ), a Liga union, rejected the offer submitted by the Economic and Transport Ministry on spur lines and wants to make a new offer.
Political Capital: The Hungary Guard has heightened the country's risk level.
Hungarian Guard action, established in August with support from the Movement for a Righter Hungary, has raised the political risk level of Hungary and the whole region from several aspects, according to the Risk Analysing Division of Political Capital.
The research entity issued a "risk warning" writing: the actions of the Hungarian Guard are threatening the existing ethnic tensions between Gypsy and non-Gypsy residents of Hungary, which could become very toxic in the short term, leading to ethnic conflicts that could turn violent.
The main reason for this is that Hungary Guard's political strategy seems to be aimed at provoking such action, the research institutes added.
This is the result of one of Hungary's most serious failures: "The main actors in public life turned the public debate of Roma issues to radical and extremist political forces, who have built a political strategy out of Gypsy-Hungarian differences."
This, Political Capital believes, has intensified the problem, making normal dialogue impossible, reinforcing the extremists, and heightening the likelihood of violent conflicts.
In addition, the research institutes believe that the intensive domestic and international media attention to Hungarian Guard actions has "significantly damaged Hungary's international image, particularly regarding belief in the country's stability and sophistication of its democracy."
The authors point out that the increasing publicity and political fuel to the re-organization of radical and far right groups in Hungary starting in the autumn of 2006 have been part of the reason why several national self-defense alliances were established in the summer of 2007.
These groups are known as civic organizations, but openly declare that they are preparing their members for defensive - including armed - tasks (e.g. disaster management, national defence, law enforcement) while declaring that they are unfit for the role.
All these moves have been made in a configuration that relies on society's anti-politics and anti-political-party mood to hide various political ambitions under a political veil.
In other words, their focus on the civic nature of their actions and their choice of the association as their organizational form are not merely ruse to sidestep legal pitfalls to registration with the courts, but also part of a political strategy.
According to the analysis, the activity of the Hungarian Guard is heightening the risk of damage to our relations with our neighbors.
Recent months several of Hungary's neighbors have cited the Hungarian Guard as a potential threat. The ultranationalist political players among some of these neighbors have referred to the establishment of the Hungarian Guard as an argument to justify their own anti-Hungarian policies.
All of these factors influence the political stability of the region, it adds.
The research institutes note that the establishment of the Hungarian Guard is not a unique phenomenon in Central and Eastern Europe, and as such it heightens the political risk for the region.
It notes that the operation of the Hungary Guard is similar to that of the Bulgarian National Guard, established in August 2007 by the far right Bulgarian National Union. (BNU).
The serious fighting between Roma and non-Roma in a Sofia district (Krasna Polyana) was the cause of the Bulgarian guard.
BNU used the disturbances to build its guard, claiming that its goal was "national self-defense."
They argue that for the past 17 years Bulgaria has been subject to "Gypsy terror," in which the government was unable to act and remained indifferent, Political Capital reported.
The initiative caused heated debate in Bulgarian public, it added.
The signs of ethnic conflict have become more serious, the analysts wrote.
Since the Hungarian Guard has so far acted quite similarly to the Bulgarian National Guard, it is possible that the Roma community of Hungary could respond to the threat by organizing their own self-defense, which is quite possible, according to Political Capital.
Political Capital research manager Attila Juhász answered to a question from the MTI Hungarian wire service by saying risk analysis was one of the research institutes' main activities.
Each year, he said, they publish risk analyses, and if they discover any factor that might alter risks, they advise public opinion by publishing a risk warning, as they have now done.
Holidays: Not everyone gets to enjoy the red letter days.
Hungarian law names red letter days specifically, and reorganizing working days to increase the number of days off around the holidays has become a general practice, but next year we will not see much reorganization.
Holidays are not uniform in EU or USA either.
The Hungary legal system distinguishes between national holidays, state/bank holidays and non-working days.
Non-working days are mostly religious holidays and anniversary of significant historical events.
Hungarian New Year's Eve and Day are both non-working days - the first if no other reason than to recover from New Year's Eve festivities.
There are totally eleven red-letter days in each calendar year.
March 15 is a national holiday commemorating the revolution of 1848 and October 23 commemorates the 1956 revolution.
July 20 marks the founding of the country, and May Day is Labour Day.
In addition, Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas are each two-day holidays.
Since our state, national or even religious holidays rarely fall on the weekend, it has become common to reorganize the working week when there is only one workday between the holiday and the weekend.
The long weekend has a price, which is to have to spend the preceding or succeeding Saturday at work or school.
The Minister of Labour has issued decrees on the days we have to work to get extra day off between the holiday and weekend.
The decree covers all employers and all workers they employ, including civil servants and public employees.
It does not cover staff in facilities, businesses or institutions that regularly operate round-the-clock or where staff work 24/7.
The last change this year will be around the end of the year holidays, as we have learned that most people find ways to take off the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve, either by saving vacation days or by working longer hours before and after the holidays and taking a longer vacation time.
Next year most holidays will occur in midweek, so less manipulation of the calendar than this year.
The first re-organization of the working week will occur to accommodate May Day and allow working people to have four consecutive days off.
Saturday April 26 will be a workday, and in exchange, Friday, May 2 will be a day off.
The working week will be re-started around the October 23 holiday. Saturday, October 18 will be a workday so people may have Friday, October 24 off.
