Six little things you can annoy your colleagues with
The emails we forget to send, the voice-mail messages we never get, the white lies we tell and no longer notice - all can colour our work life.
The question is whether you get used to the minor annoyances or pick up the gauntlet and deliberately avoid dubious situations that can irritate others.
A few tips.
"Sorry, I forgot to tell you that marketing was looking for you," says one of your colleagues.
You missed a meeting because of that?
In a best case scenario, he or she will apologize and try to mend things.
In most cases the matter ends with an apology.
Before you get into a situation where you have to apologize, consider what you might do to give your colleagues a few unpleasant minutes, and then deliberately try to avoid doing them.
Do you steal things that do not belong to you?
Nothing is more annoying than reaching for a document, piece of office equipment or phone which turns out to not be there.
You remember having left your stapler on your desk but it appears to have wings.
Maybe you see the pen you thought you lost on your colleague's desk.
Please do not take anything away from a colleague's desk without asking. They have every right to be angry if you take off with their belongings.
Do not pocket office envelopes or Post-It notes. It can be very irritating if they run out prematurely, especially if you are the one who needs one immediately.
Do you gossip about your colleagues' private lives?
There is no good way to stop gossip that has already spread.
Who is doing what with whom?
Where and why?
There is no need to spread your information (assumptions) about your colleague all through the house!
If someone shares his or her most intimate secrets with you, do not abuse that trust!
When a colleague is out, do not discuss his or her private life with others, even if they also know what the person has done.
Do you call in sick when you are not?
When you call in sick because of a splitting headache, or when you just feel good, think about the workers who will have to take up the slack and get all your urgent tasks done by deadline.
Do not play dirty with your colleagues!
If you know beforehand that you are not going to be in, or if something causes you to stay home for a day, tell your colleagues and supervisor to know.
Humming, hooting, phoning
How have you ever been totally immersed in your work, only to lose your focus because of gffawing colleagues?
You have ever been unwilling to hear a phone conversation you would have preferred not to hear?
Do not disturb your colleagues by gumming, singing or loud talking (right over their head), tapping rhythms with your feet, continuous cursing or loudly voiced complaints.
All of these things can be irritating, even if people are not concentrating on a project (writing, planning or organizing something).
Do you blame others for your mistakes?
If something is not prepared by deadline, if you forgot to send out an important letter or pass on a message, do not blame others for your forgetfulness!
Do not blame chaos in the office - even if they exist - or your loud colleagues!
Accept that you made the mistake and someone else suffered the consequences, and do what you can to make amends!
Ask how you can repair the damage and do what you need to make things right!
Office too much like a second home?
Track suit and slippers: quite comfortable when you are home, but they are not office wear!
Do not dress for leisure at work, even if your job allows it.
Do not be sloppy. Show respect for your colleagues and yourself by dressing tastefully - and elegantly if your job requires it - to work.
