hvg.hu asked Balázs Zságer.
hvg.hu: The question this new hit song raises is how culty your music has remained?
Zságer: I do not see much meaning in the term cult music.
I think there are two light music categories; not mainstream and underground and not alternative and pop, but commerce and honest.
So-called alternative or underground music can be dull and uninspiring and produced for the sole purpose of boosting sales, which places it in the commerce category.
While a good pop song can be inspired by honest motives.
The attitudes of the recipients operate in that spirit, irrespective of language and national boundaries.
hvg.hu: Do you see any difference in the reception of domestic and international audiences as far as your music goes?
B.Zs: Light music has more tradition abroad, especially west of here.
Then, older people also come to concerts, not just teens and twenty-somethings.
The more attention is paid to changes in the genre because they consider it a part of contemporary culture.
hvg.hu: What role does the audience play in your work?
Do the people who listen to your music and the number of listening people make a difference?
B.Zs: It is good to see more and more people at our concerts.
