The six-voice choir - of Sena, Edina Kutzora, Judie Jay, Bori Péterfy, Enikő Hodosi [Neo], and Juci Németh - was named Underground Divas.
hvg.hu: Is the result exactly as you expected it, or did girls play a role in shaping the sound?
B.Zs: It was a very long instrumental version, but then when we were making the CD together, we started to feel that we needed to add something.
The Chordal sequence was asking for a vocal section.
Then I sang the melody onto the instrumental, and that was how the girls learned it afterwards.
The whole thing came to me all at once and it was shockingly spontaneous.
The Divas were necessary to make it work.
It never would have been this powerful in my voice.
hvg.hu: The girls seemed to be secondary on both the disc and at the concert.
There is no solo (except Judy Jay's tiny one), they have no separate role, they sing completely in unison, and they do not outsing the music, so it is not as if they were singing to subordinate musical accompaniment.
On stage, they stood at the back.
What was all that deliberate?
B.Zs.: The reason why they stood at the back of the stage was technical problems.
It was deliberate.
The whole number was about forgetting our egos for a time, not thinking about who came from where and where they are headed, and simply letting them wings, the wings of love, lift us up.
The purpose of the song was to give others the feeling of the enthusiasm we had when the song was born.
hvg.hu: Who gave you the most work?
B.Zs: No really, as far as the process of musical creation was concerned - but some of them gave us a hard time with the arrangement.
Examples are Dorian Gray's Dilemma, where I play on a concert piano, or Rock'n'Roll Goes To The Girls, where the groove would not work for a long time - but everything eventually ended up fitting.
hvg.hu: What's your own favourite number on this CD?
B.Zs: It keeps changing with every concert, especially now that I have already left the CD.
At the moment it's Prophet is A Fool, Escape from Earth, and Never the Same.
