Congress approves the transposition of Mifid that occurred on November 1st.
Following its parliamentary proceedings, which ended today with the partial vote of the Congress on the amendments to the project in the Senate, the government has submitted to public hearing the regulation that will develop the new law, with the aim of coming into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of different groups agreed on the efforts of deputies and senators to negotiate and agree the best legislation for guaranteeing the protection of investors and regulating the organization activities so that the markets work efficiently.
The Mifid, which amends the Securities Market Act, involves modernization of financial markets, strengthening investor protection, improving the supervisory powers of the National Commission for the Mercado de Valores (CNMV), and promoting cooperation among the European Union’s supervisors.
The new regulations will grant financial advice to specialized companies and to natural or legal individuals, and creates a new type of financial advisory companies (ESIS), which include stock firms, brokers and portfolio management firms.
In addition, it expands the number of systems available for the execution of financial operations, so included in the regulation are secondary markets, multilateral trading systems, and internalization systems of orders, these will compete with the current stock market managers.
The law also requires investment services companies to disclose key details of their business profile, risk exposure and risk management, and to keep a registry of all their operations to facilitate the supervision by the CNMV.
In their passage through the Economic Affairs Committee of the Congress, several modifications were introduced, most notably securitised debts should be considered as a "complex" financial instrument due to its high risk for the investor, which has been evidenced by what happened with high risk American mortgages (subprime).
In addition, the transposition used the directive to legally define the functions that can develop graduates in Economics and Finance in 30 years after the declaration of 1977, that defines the professional functions reserved for professional economists.
The Senate promotes the development of new roles in the financial sector, such as the financial advisor, who will work for hire or reward, not require SEC approval and will be able to provide his services and marketing products to customers at several investment firms at the same time.
