New Russia-Ukraine gas row fears
The new gas price dispute is brewing between Ukraine and Russia, raising the risk that Russian exports of the fuel to western Europe may be affected.
Most of Russia's gas exports to the European Union (EU) are piped through Ukraine and any row between the two countries is watched closely.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow raises the price it has to pay for gas it will charge Russia higher transit fees.
The previous dispute between the two last year reduced EU supplies.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes as the Ukrainian government and Russia's state-owned gas monopoly, Gazprom, try to agree on how much Ukraine must pay for Russian gas in 2008.
Gazprom says it will have to charge Ukraine more as it has agreed to pay up to 50% extra in 2008 for gas it sourced from neighbouring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean Ukraine having to pay 40% more for its imports from Gazprom.
'We need to use our arguments as one of the top gas transit states in the talks'.
The changes in gas prices should be linked to our arguments about the levels of transit fees to western Europe via Ukraine.
The last major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev saw Gazprom cut supplies to Ukraine in January 2006.
The result was a knock-on fall in exports to western Europe, which sharply pushed prices.
Russian gas accounts for one quarter of European Union's supplies.
Russia has the world's largest gas stocks, but much of it is under-developed.
As a result, Gazprom supplements its own supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other central Asian former Soviet nations.
NHS must check foreign workers
Scottish NHS boards need to improve criminal records checks for employees outside Europe, a watchdog has said.
The recommendation from Auditor General Robert Black came after a foreign doctor in Scotland was linked to the June airport attack.
Black also raised concerns that NHS Scotland had no accurate picture of the number of overseas staff it had.
The report pointed out other key checks were properly carried out across a sample of five health authorities.
The general auditor looked at recruiting staff outside European Economic Area countries, after the Glasgow Airport attack.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after a Jeep was driven into the main terminal building.
The doctor was one of three doctors who appeared at the Old Bailey by video link in October, charged in connection with the suspected car bomb attempts in the UK.
NHS boards are expected to conduct pre-employment checks on overseas staff to ensure they have the qualifications, experience and authorisation to work in the UK.
Although Scots health boards use Disclosure Scotland to perform criminal records checks, the agency has no jurisdiction to obtain such information outside Britain.
The auditor general's report has now advised that the board should take on Criminal Records Bureau guidance, which helps employers with checks in several countries.
Although some of the personnel records had evidence of these checks, this is not routinely done.
The report highlights areas where the system can be improved to ensure accurate information on the number of overseas NHS staff.
British Medical Association Scotland chairman Dr Peter Terry said it was "extremely unlikely" that pre-employment checks could identify potential NHS employees who may commit future terrorist acts.
The report suggests that current pre-employment checks are working well in NHS Scotland and it is unclear what added value the recommendations will deliver.
Scotland health authorities have currently 1,161 overseas staff, mostly doctors and nurses.
The auditor general warned the number could be higher, partly because boards had difficulty identifying which staff were on indefinite leave to stay.
The investigation also found that established check procedures at NHS authorities in Ayrshire and Arran, Grampian and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian were largely being followed.
These included passport, work permit and qualification checks.
The Scottish Government is currently revising its policy and guidance on pre-employment checks for overseas staff in the NHS.
Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: “I was keen to have this work carried out in the wake of the terror attack on Glasgow Airport.
The report added that the Scottish Government, in collaboration with health boards, would consider the recommendations of the report and ensure best practice was reflected in updated guidance on pre-employment checks for all staff - including those from overseas.
