Venus climate may be a window into future for Earth
Venus may have once been a pleasant place to live, scientists said yesterday.
The planet is even more like a wayward twin of Earth than was previously thought.
Venus is Earth's close planetary neighbor.
The two worlds are about the same size and occupy similar orbits, but Venus is slightly closer to the Sun.
Billions of years ago, Venus would have had conditions similar to those on Earth and may even have been habitable, scientists now believe.
The runaway carbon dioxide greenhouse effect, atmospheric erosion by solar radiation, and a slower rotation rate sent Venus to a different development path.
Today the planet is stripped of water, has a surface temperature hot enough to melt lead and is threatened by Hurricane-force winds and lightning storms.
The findings from the European Space Agency's Venus Express probe, which has been studying the planet for a year, offer a sobering view of how Earth might develop given severe climate change.
The mission leaders of Venus Express, Professor Fred Taylor of Oxford University's department of physics, a member of the Venus Express mission, said: "It is becoming clear why the climate on Venus is so different from the Earth when the planets themselves are otherwise quite similar.
The new data allow us to construct a scenario in which Venus started out like the Earth, possibly with a habitable environment, billions of years ago.
