Pains in work
Gordon Brown has discovered yet another hole to fall into; his way out of it remains the same.
As British politics go, this one is not particularly juicy.
No honours seem to have been sold, no politician's Paris hotel bills picked up, no extra-marital toes swollen.
The revelation that a rich businessman disguised his contributions to the Labour Party of more than £650,000 ($1.3m) over four years under other people's names, and that the party failed to report it is one that the eminent Gordon Brown could have done without.
The expectation was that he would provide a strong, efficient government.
Instead, as Vince Cable, the Liberal Democrats' increasingly witty stand-in leader, Mr Brown has changed from Stalin to Mr Bean.
The cack-handed rescue of Northern Rock, a troubled bank, showed regulatory weakness and poor judgment under fire.
Thought-out proposals to change the tax code have gathered business groups together against the government.
The loss of 25m people's personal details revealed unimaginable administrative bungling.
The trio of retired generals launched a mutiny in the Lords, protesting against cuts in military spending: being a military minister is, they claim, a part-time job.
The multifaceted donations from David Abrahams, Labour's general secretary (and previous head of compliance) have already resigned.
None of this means that Mr Brown is irrevocably headed for the exit.
It can reach a tipping point after which they find it impossible to govern.
People do not like nor trust politicians, but usually withdraw their disbelief when a new lot takes over.
Once it seems clear that a Prime Minister is unlikely to improve things, and may not be around for long, the civil service starts leaking; cabinet ministers start briefing; the press searches for bad news; and government becomes defensive and unfocused.
In one way, Mr Brown's position is particularly difficult, because unlike other political leaders he cannot claim to be a new broom.
Though he would like to disown Tony Blair, he was his senior lieutenant.
The problems with Northern Rock and the tax-authority records are linked to decisions Mr Brown made as Secretary of the Exchequer.
If he was not directly involved in Blairish mishaps - such as the long "cash for peerages investigation into political-party funding - voters may assume he was.
The situation is not as bad as it looks.
The mistakes are not as appalling as the Tories are making out.
As with Mr Bean, no one has died or been swindled outright.
The remedy, painful though it may be, is to provide reliable, sound and sometimes brutal government.
The new fuss about political donations is a good example.
The Garboesque Mr Abrahams, who compares his donations to his charitable giving, says he wished no public recognition for his giving.
It may be so, but the decision was not his to make.
The laws against anonymity for big political contributors are clear and they exist for a clear reason: the public is entitled to know who may be buying access to those who rule the land.
The lawyer, who says he knew of the arrangement but does not believe it was illegal, will face close questioning.
The evidence is that Mr Brown is not involved, although the majority of the payments were made after he took office in June.
The Prime Minister has done half of the job.
The committee was quick to condemn the breach of law, but he diluted that confidence by reaching for a familiar tool, a committee of investigation into the matter - led by a retired bishop and a judge.
This case, the "lessons to be learned" are not complicated.
If the law has been broken, it is a matter for the police.
Beyond that, there are other things that Mr Brown needs to do, such as finding a permanent chair for the independent Committee on Public Health Standards, which has been without one for six months, and pressing ahead with genuine reform of political-party funding.
The latter would require hard-up Labour to co-operate with the Tories and possibly give up its special financial relationship with the unions - bitter pills for a partisan like Mr Brown.
But he should face some partisan facts.
The Conservatives now have a decent lead in the polls; he has two years to get back voters; and only one way he can secure a victory is through unimpeachable probity and solid competence.
