The subprime mortgage crisis is infecting America's credit card market?
When blood is in water, it is natural that dorsal fins swirl excitedly.
The housing market is aging, and players are looking at the country's credit card market.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs believe that credit card losses could reach $$99 billion if contagion spreads from subprime mortgages to other consumer credit.
Symptoms of strain are clearly visible.
The increase in both the charge-off and delinquency rates is measured by the share of balances that are uncollectible or more than 30 days late.
HSBC announced last month that it had taken a $1.4 billion charge in its American consumer-finance business, mainly because of weakness among card borrowers.
It is too early to panic, though.
Charges and damages are still low.
According to Moody's, a rating agency, the third quarter delinquency rate of 3.89% was almost half of the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be partly explained by technical factors.
The change in America's personal-bankruptcy laws in 2005 led to a sudden decline in bankruptcy filings, which in turn account for a large chunk of credit card losses.
The industry also reports solid payment rates, which show how much of their debt consumers pay off each month.
And confidence in credit-card asset-backed securities is pretty firm despite paralysis in other areas of structured finance.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup, a research firm, predicts that issuance volumes for 2007 will end up being 25% higher than last year.
Direct channels of infection between subprime-mortgage crisis and the credit-card market are certainly present: consumers are likely to load up on credit-card debt now that home-equity loans are drying up.
The card issuers look at cash flow rather than asset values, so falling house prices do not necessarily cause a change in borrowers' creditworthiness.
They may even work to issuers' advantage.
The incentives for consumers to keep paying the mortgage decrease if properties are less than the value of the loan; card debt rises up on the list of repayment priorities.
However, card issuers are also able to respond much quicker and flexibly to stormy conditions than mortgage lenders, by changing interest rates or altering credit limits.
It theoretically reduces the risk of rapid repricing of assets.
Gary Perlin, Capital One's chief financial Officer.
If a sudden subprime-style meltdown in credit-card market is unlikely, sustained downturn is much more real.
