Three British bankers who were set to go to trial for their role in a fraudulent scheme with former Enron Chief Financial Officer Andrew Fastow have changed their pleas to guilty Wednesday.
David Beringham, Giles Darby and Gary Mulgrew were originally found innocent to seven counts of wire fraud for allegedly colluding with Fastow in a secret financial scam in 2000.
The two were set to go on trial in January.
The two parties each pleaded guilty to one count of wire fraud.
The three former executives at Greenwich NatWest, a unit of Royal Bank of Scotland Group PLC, became a cause for worldwide recognition throughout extradition procedures that lasted two years.
In the United States, the case is a loose end of an investigation launched after Enron's 2001 collapse.
Initial charges against them in 2002 alerted Fastow that he was a target of the government's investigation into Enron's downfall.
The indictment against the bankers is called the "NatWest Three" and alleges they came to Houston in 2000 to prepare a fraudulent scheme with Fastow and his former top aide Michael Kopper.
Greenwich NatWest had invested in a subsidiary of an Enron partnership controlled by Fastow, who was the architect of a myriad of fraudulent Enron schemes that helped drive the plunge into bankruptcy.
The bank had valued its interest in the subsidiary at zero, but the three British men knew it had significant value.
A company under Kopper's control acquired the bank's interest in the subsidiary for $1 million.
The bankers paid Kopper $250,000 for interest in this company.
The indictment states that Fastow falsely represented to Enron that the energy company would pay $20 million to Greenwich NatWest for its shares in the subsidiary.
The $20 million actually went to the British bankers, Fastow and others.
The bankers got $7.3 million, while Fastow, Kopper and others skimmed about $12.3 million, according to the indictment.
In January 2004, Fastow was found guilty to two counts of conspiracy for his role in Enron's collapse.
The British trio was arrested three months later.
Fastow is serving a six-year prison sentence in a federal prison in Louisiana.
Kopper is serving a three year, one month sentence at a facility in Texarkana.
Each of the three British men have been free on $1 million bonds that required them to live in the United States pending trial.
Enron, once the seventh-largest company, collapsed in December 2001 after years of accounting tricks could no longer hide billions of debt or make failing ventures look profitable.
