Richard Gere Is Not Cynical enough
The Hunting Party"and "Mörderischer Frieden" make two more films about Balkan War.
No one of them is convincing.
either the concepts are too much focused on action sequences and gunfire, or they are too dull.
Even Richard Gere, in “The Hunting Party,” cannot change that.
The good news first: Bosnian war criminals Karadzic and Mladic may still be hiding in the Balkan mountains.
The most beautiful man of the eighties has been lost, after too many very trivial roles in feel-good films for women and too many Buddhist press conferences have exhausted any desire to watch him.
The best reason why we might want to watch The Hunting Party is Richard Gere. (The full German title is The Hunting Party – When the Hunter becomes a hunter)
The performance is delightfully tongue-in-cheek. Essentially, his war reporter Simon Hunt is whom Gere could have ended up as, had fate and the film industry not been so kind to him.
The Hunting Party, along with the German production "Mörderischer Frieden,"which also debuts this week, is merely a continuation of the endless line of failed Balkan War movies.
"Mörderischer Frieden" is a very quick film about two German soldiers in Kosovo (Adrian Topol, Max Riemelt) who rescue a Serbian woman from Kosovan snipers - and one of them promptly falls in love with her.
The fact that the Serbs are not portrayed as the sole source of all evil is to be appreciated, but the film, in its TV-like shallowness, quickly falls into a few action sequences.
What remains is something like the German car-chase TV show "Alarm for Cobra 11" only with war taking place.
The Hunting Party, meanwhile, is almost like exhibit A in the investigation on why there has never been a good Balkan War movie.
With another director and another screenwriter (Richard Shepard is both), and at another time, the story of three US war reporters committed to track down Serbian war criminal supreme "The Fox" might have ended up being a new "Apocalypse Now."
The stories are quite similar: In both, small teams enter the forest to do something the military cannot do, and in both, the result is a journey into madness.
The reasons why The Hunting Party fails is that Simon Hunt is not allowed to be simply the run-down cynic with a heart of gold.
No, the script also has to saddle him with a romantic relationship with a Bosnian muslim woman who is later killed.
The Hunting Party goes off the rails when the reporters, in fast forward motion, achieve in the last five minutes what NATO, CIA and all the world’s bounty hunters have not achieved in five years: To catch the war criminal and leave him to the just revenge of the Bosnian Muslims.
This is so bad that you want to appeal to the International Court of Justice at The Hague on the basis of crimes against cinematic logic.
The film’s concern is actually a deeply human one.
It wants to condemn the fact that Karadzic and Mladic are still free as they please, and it suspects the Americans and the French (apparently agree here) of not being overly concerned with their pursuit due to secret political horse-trading.
Good intentions and evil are so similar that a popular poem by Brecht appears.
In the poem, the wooden mask of an Asian demon resting on the poet’s work desk is described: “With sympathy I look at the swollen veins on the forehead, suggesting how hard it is to be evil.
The Hunting Party has the same swollen head, in that case suggesting how hard it is to be good.
The problem is not limited to the genre of Balkan War movie.
The recent report in this paper reported that all Hollywood Iraq movies have utterly bombed.
One could add: There has never been a good South Africa movie.
Rules of thumb: If a star actor is running around in hot spots or on the minefields of the world, the result is something like "Rangoon,"with Patricia Arquette, "Beyond Borders,"with Angelina Jolie, or "Blood Diamond,"with Leonardo DiCaprio.
Possibly, all these conflicts are too recent.
After all, years have taken before Hollywood could direct a good Holocaust movie in “Schindler’s List.”
Some film or other may still mature – Vietnam works "The Deer Hunter,""Apocalypse Now"or "Full Metal Jacket" were not exactly recognised as classics at the time.
Maybe we do not know enough about the violent world nowadays, with every instance of mass murder appearing at our homes in real time and on two screens simultaneously.
It robs screenwriters of the recklessness required to tell good stories.
The reason why “To Be or Not” or “The Great Dictator” are such good films is that Lubitsch and Chaplin did not yet know how bad the Nazi regime was.
To make good films, one must not want to be good.
Maybe a sarcastically distanced artistic view like the novelist Lawrence Norfolk’s is needed.
When asked about the parallels between his historical novel "Lemprière’s Dictionary" and the Balkan War, he replied: "Because some things never change.
Large cities will always be terribly dangerous, people will always be murdered in gruesome ways, and there will always be war in Yugoslavia.
