Those Are Warhol’s Boxes
Connecting Sweden and wooden box makes one think of Ikea, rather than Andy Warhol.
It is or is it not?
Currently wooden boxes manufactured in Sweden are casting dark shadows on Warhol’s work.
The bulk of the ninety four Brillo Boxes "Type Stockholm"listed in it are forgeries.
The Swedish newspaper Expressen asked for the authenticity of Andy Warhol’s 1968 Brillo Boxes several years ago, now internal investigation at the Moderna Museet, Stockholm, has come to the conclusion that the six "Brillo Boxes"donated to the Museum in 1995 are forgeries – as are the bulk of the nearly 100 remaining Brillo Boxes in international art market.
The history is convoluted, a complex chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Andy Warhol created his first "Brillo Boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes based on the red, white and blue design of the "Brillo"soap cardboard box.
The exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet in 1969 presented – with Warhol’s consent – hundreds of Brillo Boxes made of cardboard: For economical reasons, they were not by Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard mill.
Them were not works of art, but models – mere sample pieces.
Similarly, Warhol apparently consented to the production of small wooden Brillo Boxes in Sweden in 1968, which were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Contemporary witnesses now speak of about 15 boxes which made art and auction history as original Andy Warhol Brillo Boxes with the designation "Type Stockholm".
Some of them went for more than 100,000 dollars at auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that around 100 wooden boxes were produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, and later consigned to him by Warhol.
The 105 boxes were produced in 1990 in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
The time was when Warhol was already dead for three years.
In addition to the six Brillo Boxes belonging to the Moderna Museet, Lars Byström, Chief Conservator at the museum, examined three private Swedish owners, of which two were manufactured in Stockholm in 1968: The pressboards were first primed and sandpapered, then white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The structure of 1990 facsimiles shows that the paint was applied directly to the pressboard with a roller and without priming – and, further, that it wasn’t oil paint, but acrylic.
The six boxes are not authorised by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol’s Brillo Boxes.
The Authentication Board had already announced an investigation into the "grave allegations" made in the case of the soapboxes back in July.
However, it has been kept in a steady silence ever since.
